            <div type="glosses">
                <note xml:id="ATTENDANTSGLOSS" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">&#x201C;Though his attendants . . . northern crown&#x201D; 
                    (<title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIII">MS III</title>; <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSXI">MS XI</title>)&#x2014;</hi><persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName> 
                    perhaps means that these heavenly bodies attend on the sun by following a path close to the sun&#x02BC;s ecliptic. 
                    As the <persName type="fictional" corresp="#TUTORJJ">Tutor</persName> explains in <persName corresp="#JJ">Jeremiah Joyce</persName>&#x02BC;s <title type="book" corresp="#JOYCESCIENTIFICDIALOGUES"><hi rend="italic">Scientific Dialogues</hi></title>, the moon &#x201C;is always either in the ecliptic, 
                    or within five degrees and a third of it on one side or the other. The planets also, by which I mean, <name type="astronomical" corresp="#MERCURY">Mercury</name>, 
                    <name type="astronomical" corresp="#VENUSPLANET">Venus</name> [the &#x201C;Evening Star&#x201d;}, <name type="astronomical" corresp="#MARS">Mars</name>, <name type="astronomical" corresp="#JUPITER">Jupiter</name>, <name type="astronomical" corresp="#SATURN">Saturn</name>, and the <name type="astronomical" corresp="#URANUS">Herschel [Uranus]</name>, are never more than eight degrees distant from the line of the ecliptic&#x201D;. 
                    His pupil then asking to trace the ecliptic in relation to the fixed stars, the <persName type="fictional" corresp="#TUTORJJ">Tutor</persName> describes the constellations of the zodiac 
                    (<ref type="bibliography" target="bibliography.php#JOYCESCIENTIFICDIALOGUES"><persName corresp="#JJ">Joyce</persName>, <title type="book" corresp="#JOYCESCIENTIFICDIALOGUES"><hi rend="italic">Scientific Dialogues</hi></title></ref>, &#x201C;Of Astronomy&#x201D;, conversation 3, <title type="lesson" corresp="#JOYCESCIENTIFICDIALOGUESECLIPTIC">&#x201C;Of the Fixed Stars, and Ecliptic&#x201D;</title>, 2:28&#x2013;29). 
                    <persName corresp="#JR">Ruskin</persName>, however, does not identify constellations in the zodiac; instead, he names prominent constellations that, unlike the seasonal ones in the zodiac, 
                    remain visible throughout the year, and that are commonly chosen as starting points in lessons about the night sky. <name type="astronomical" corresp="#ORION">Orion</name> lies along the celestial equator, and therefore, in the northern hemisphere, appears high in sky for part of year, and low for the remainder. 
                    The rest are circumpolar constellations, revolving around the <name type="astronomical" corresp="#POLARIS">&#x201C;North Star&#x201d;</name> (Polaris)&#x2014;<name type="astronomical" corresp="#URSAMAJOR">Ursa Major (Great Bear)</name>, 
                    of which the <name type="astronomical" corresp="#PLOUGH">&#x201C;Plough&#x201D;</name> or <name type="astronomical" corresp="#CHARLESSWAIN">&#x201C;Charles&#x02BC;s Wain&#x201D;</name> forms a part; 
                    <name type="astronomical" corresp="#URSAMINOR">Ursa Minor (&#x201C;Lesser&#x201D; Bear)</name>; and <name type="astronomical" corresp="#CORONABOREALIS">Corona Borealis (&#x201C;Northern Crown&#x201d;)</name>.</p></note>
